  <main id="main"><header class="page-hero page-hero--light-brief"><div class="container"><div class="breadcrumbs"><a href="index.html">Home</a> / <a href="host-institutions.html">Host Institutions</a> / Who Can Host</div><span class="kicker">The host ecosystem</span><h1>Who Can Host</h1><p>NGOs, research institutes, universities, civic institutions, public-interest organizations, and approved mission-driven entities may serve as hosts.</p></div></header><nav class="anchor-nav anchor-nav--rail" aria-label="On this page"><div class="container"><a href="#focus"><span>01</span>Areas of focus</a><a href="#overview"><span>02</span>Overview</a><a href="#principles"><span>03</span>Principles</a><a href="#process"><span>04</span>How it works</a><a href="#next"><span>05</span>Next steps</a></div></nav><section class="section focus-columns" id="focus"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">The host relationship</span><h2>What a consequential host setting must provide</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Eligible hosts include nonprofits, research institutes, universities, civic institutions, public-interest organizations, and other approved entities with credible missions.</p></div><div class="focus-columns__grid"><article class="dimension-card"><span>01</span><LegacyIcon name="compass" /><h3>Nonprofits and NGOs</h3><p>Humanitarian, environmental, educational, community, cultural, and public-interest organizations.</p></article><article class="dimension-card"><span>02</span><LegacyIcon name="institution" /><h3>Research and higher education</h3><p>Institutes, laboratories, centers, universities, and field programs with suitable oversight.</p></article><article class="dimension-card"><span>03</span><LegacyIcon name="lightbulb-o" /><h3>Civic institutions</h3><p>Organizations advancing public administration, access, resilience, policy, law, or community capacity.</p></article><article class="dimension-card"><span>04</span><LegacyIcon name="handshake-o" /><h3>Mission-driven entities</h3><p>Approved institutions able to demonstrate public purpose, responsible governance, and a credible opportunity.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section brief-overview" id="overview"><div class="container"><div class="brief-heading"><div class="prose"><span class="eyebrow">For Host Institutions</span><h2>Mission-driven institutions prepared to support a Fellow</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Eligible hosts include nonprofits, research institutes, universities, civic institutions, public-interest organizations, and other approved entities with credible missions.</p><p>Institutional type alone is not sufficient. Qualification depends on the proposed work, organizational standing, supervision, safeguards, and capacity to uphold Society standards.</p><p>Nonprofits and NGOs establishes the point of entry; mission-driven entities defines what should remain after the immediate work is complete.</p></div><span class="brief-mark" aria-hidden="true">USF / BRIEF</span></div><div class="fact-strip"><div><span>Central question</span><strong>Mission-driven institutions prepared to support a Fellow</strong></div><div><span>Opening priorities</span><strong>Nonprofits and NGOs; Research and higher education</strong></div><div><span>Extended scope</span><strong>Civic institutions; Mission-driven entities</strong></div></div></div></section><section class="section" id="principles"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">Conditions for trust</span><h2>The responsibilities of a qualified host</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Responsible hosting requires a real need, capable supervision, and mutual clarity from the outset.</p></div><div class="principle-pillars"><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">01</span><h3>A credible need</h3><p>The opportunity should respond to real institutional or public-interest work rather than create an ornamental role. In this context, consider nonprofits and ngos.</p></article><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">02</span><h3>Responsible support</h3><p>A Fellow needs a designated supervisor, appropriate access, timely feedback, and a safe working setting. In this context, consider research and higher education.</p></article><article class="card card--numbered"><span class="card__number">03</span><h3>Mutual value</h3><p>The appointment should respect the Fellow&#x27;s capabilities while producing useful value for the mission and institution. In this context, consider civic institutions.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section" id="process"><div class="container"><div class="section-intro"><span class="eyebrow">From intent to practice</span><h2>Building a strong host relationship</h2><div class="rule"></div><p>Good appointments begin before a Fellow arrives. Hosts clarify the work, establish support, and agree on what responsible completion looks like.</p></div><div class="steps"><article class="step"><h3>Propose</h3><p>Describe the mission, institutional need, likely work, intended benefit, and responsible owner. Here, attend to nonprofits and ngos: Humanitarian, environmental, educational, community, cultural, and public-interest organizations.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Qualify</h3><p>Confirm organizational standing, supervision, resources, role clarity, and alignment with Society standards. Here, attend to research and higher education: Institutes, laboratories, centers, universities, and field programs with suitable oversight.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Match and shape</h3><p>Align the opportunity with a Fellow&#x27;s capabilities and turn it into a realistic appointment plan. Here, attend to civic institutions: Organizations advancing public administration, access, resilience, policy, law, or community capacity.</p></article><article class="step"><h3>Support and close</h3><p>Provide feedback throughout the work, review outcomes, and capture lessons at completion. Here, attend to mission-driven entities: Approved institutions able to demonstrate public purpose, responsible governance, and a credible opportunity.</p></article></div></div></section><section class="section layout-cta" id="next"><div class="container"><div class="cta"><div><h2>Shape an opportunity the Society can assess</h2><p>Begin with nonprofits and ngos, then define a contribution your capabilities or institution can support.</p></div><div class="actions"><a class="button button--gold" href="submit-opportunity.html">Submit an opportunity</a><a class="button button--outline" href="become-a-host.html">Become a Host</a></div></div><div class="atlas-links"><aside class="related-panel"><span class="eyebrow">Continue exploring</span><h3>Related pathways</h3><ul class="related-list"><li><a href="host-institutions.html">Host overview</a></li><li><a href="host-standards.html">Host standards</a></li><li><a href="appointment-model.html">Appointment model</a></li></ul></aside></div></div></section></main>

